Lapses because of holidays and illness do not jeopardize adherence, but dissatisfaction with the content (intensity) of the program and physical limitations do. Especially in moderate-intensity programs, such as an aerobic walking program, exercises tailored to the individual should be offered to prevent dropout and improve attendance. Individually tailored exercises could also be a solution for health complaints and limitations that prevent the elderly from participating in exercise programs. Because participants who reported clear benefits were more likely to continue participation in the exercise programs, feedback by instructors on subjective indicators could be worthwhile.

